# gooseclaw session context
# loaded once at session start. identity files inlined via @file syntax.
# identity-data is a symlink to /data/identity/ (Railway volume).

# !! CRITICAL: if soul.md below contains "ONBOARDING_NEEDED", you MUST
# !! search the knowledge base for the onboarding flow and run it IMMEDIATELY.
# !! Do NOT respond casually. Do NOT process the user's message normally.
# !! Start with the onboarding greeting. This is your highest priority.

# core system instructions (always in context — behavioral rules, not reference docs)
@identity-data/system-core.md

# identity files (agent personality + user profile — EVOLVING, clean data only)
@identity-data/soul.md
@identity-data/user.md

# runtime context
Per-turn critical rules are in turn-rules.md (injected via MOIM, always visible).

# knowledge base (semantic vector search for system docs, memory, procedures)
# System procedures, platform docs, schemas, and runtime facts are stored in
# a ChromaDB vector database. Use the Knowledge MCP extension to access them:
#
# knowledge_search(query, type?, limit?, since?) - Semantic search across all knowledge.
#   Types: fact, procedure, preference, integration, schema
#   since: optional ISO date filter, e.g. "2026-03-17" (only chunks created on/after)
#   Example: knowledge_search("how to store credentials", type="procedure")
#   Example: knowledge_search("project updates", since="2026-03-18")
#
# knowledge_upsert(key, content, type, refs?) - Store or update a runtime fact.
#   Automatically tracks created_at and updated_at timestamps.
#   Example: knowledge_upsert("integration.slack", "Slack webhook at ...", "integration")
#
# knowledge_get(key) - Exact key lookup (faster than search when you know the key).
#   Returns timestamps (created_at, updated_at) in the output.
#   Example: knowledge_get("system.rules.credentials-and-security")
#
# knowledge_delete(key) - Delete a runtime chunk by key. System chunks cannot be deleted.
#   Example: knowledge_delete("integration.old-service")
#
# knowledge_recent(limit?) - Get most recently created/updated chunks, newest first.
#   Use this when asked "what did you store recently?" or "show latest entries".
#   Example: knowledge_recent(5)
#
# Do NOT read system.md, memory.md, or onboarding.md directly.
# Do NOT write facts, integrations, or preferences to user.md or memory.md.
# Use knowledge_upsert to store ALL new facts, integrations, and learned information.
# Use knowledge_search to find relevant procedures, facts, and integrations on demand.
# Use knowledge_recent when the user asks about recently stored entries or wants a timeline.
